Odessa City-Centre Evacuation Model
WHAT IS IT?
The Odessa Model is an agent-based Decision Support System pilot designed to study and optimise civilian-evacuation mobility during geopolitical-conflict disruptions to critical infrastructure. It represents a unique pilot application of the AntifragiCity DSS framework specifically adapted to the mobility needs during current geopolitical conflicts, where disruptions to critical infrastructure extend beyond environmental hazards to include systemic threats to civilian safety .
The model serves three purposes:
Capture the city-centre evacuation topology of Odessa — the entire road network of the city centre, including building passages and pathways in parks, sourced from OpenStreetMaps and processed in QGIS 3.40, plus the locations and capacities of the bomb shelters currently available in the city of Odessa, as mapped by the local municipality (reference 54) 
Simulate the second phase of an evacuation plan, in which civilians already gathered at the shelters are instructed to proceed with their evacuation from the area, after a port-area attack that has triggered the operational response 
Test responder-based interventions (R0–R3) that mobilise autonomous agents to locate and collect vulnerable persons through secured corridors, evaluating how responder routing and dispatch topology affect evacuation rates during the vulnerable-sub-population's exponentially longer transit times 
A distinctive constraint of the model is that the city evacuation plans were not publicly available; therefore, the rendered evacuation points were assumed for modelling purposes Despite this assumed-coordinates limitation, the validation in the source deliverable demonstrates that the model correctly distinguishes between routing protocols — the discriminating gap between R1's 30.77% and R3's 95%+ vulnerable-evacuation rate within 60 minutes is cited as one of the lines of evidence that confirm the model correctly ranks intervention protocols .HOW IT WORKS
(what rules the agents use to create the overall behavior of the model)
The semantic ontology (Figure 5.18 in the source deliverable) is multimodal and equity-aware, with examined networks' edges modelled as links, and nodes — intersections, shelters and evacuation points — as stationary agents. Dynamic agents are civilians who can then select their transport mode towards the evacuation point and transform accordingly into the corresponding agent, namely a 'pedestrian' or a 'car' .

The Network Underlay
The agent-based model integrates the entire road network of the city centre, including building passages and pathways in parks, which were imported from OpenStreetMaps and processed in QGIS 3.40 . The model also integrates the locations and capacities of the bomb shelters currently available in the city of Odessa, as mapped by the local municipality (reference 54) 
This finer-grained graph — extending down to building passages and park pathways — is critical because:
It captures escape corridors beyond the primary road network, which is essential when primary road segments are at capacity or partially obstructed during the second evacuation phase 
It provides a denser set of stationary-agent (shelter, intersection, evacuation-point) nodes on which respondent-screening logic can be run at each tick 
2. The Agents
The model's ontology distinguishes two dynamic agent breeds and three stationary-agent structures 
Agent type	Role in the model
Residents	Dynamic agents that reside at shelters until they select their transport mode; the canonical shelter-confined population. Residents can transform into pedestrian or car agents on mode choice 

Pedestrians / Cars	Dynamic agents generated from residents through the transformation rule; they traverse the city-centre graph via shortest-path routing on the corresponding network 

Intersections	Stationary agents holding the road-network state of the city centre .

Shelters	Stationary agents carrying the capacity attribute mapped from the local municipality (reference 54) 

Evacuation points	Stationary agents whose coordinates were assumed for modelling purposes, since the city evacuation plans were not publicly available 

Responders	Autonomous agents introduced in the response strategies that locate and collect vulnerable population to facilitate their safe transit through secured corridors, thereby mitigating the exposure of high-risk individuals 

Vulnerability is propagated into the agent layer by the UI's vulnerability-share slider, with the vulnerable group composed of people with disabilities, mobility impairments, age extremes, disadvantaged and socio-economic backgrounds, all of whom are assigned lower transit velocities 
3. Behavioural Rules
Residents housed in shelters are kept stationary until they receive the evacuation instruction; once triggered, they select their transport mode (pedestrian or car) and transform accordingly into the corresponding dynamic agent 
Pedestrians and cars navigate the city-centre graph using the A* algorithm, which is invoked continuously to re-evaluate these trajectories, ensuring agents adapt to real-time road accessibility shifts such as path obstructions or saturation 
Under the in-simulation statement that all the evacuees are assumed to comply with the given instructions and find the shortest path to their destination, at the expense of congestion or reduced travel speed (per reference 55), the model maintains high-fidelity compliance while still letting congestion reduce speed where it would in reality 
Vulnerable agents are assigned lower transit velocities so that without any intervention, these population groups require exponentially longer time to reach the evacuation points 
The response strategies involve the mobilization of the responders to locate and assist these individuals through prioritized extraction 
4. KPI Computation
The model exports the KPIs defined in Deliverable D2.3, with the following Odessa-specific signature extracted from the cross-pilot KPI results table 
KPI	Odessa-specific signature
Throughput (M)	Responder-based strategies sustain evacuee flow; R3 keeps the vulnerable evacuation rate above the general-population curve .

Efficiency (S)	A*-based rerouting retains efficiency under saturation; auxiliary ferry-type links are not part of the inland evacuation graph .

Redundancy (R)	Decentralised dispatch base (R3) preserves redundancy by avoiding a bottleneck at the centralised evacuation point .

Entropy / Network distribution (Q)	Stabilised by multi-base dispatch (R3); narrow single-base dispatch (R0) yields fluctuating rates .

Equity / satisfaction dimension	R0 ignores spatial distribution of vulnerable → acceptable aggregate rate but questionable casualty reduction; R1 reaches 30.77% of the vulnerable population in 60 minutes; R3 reaches >95% (also 96% as reported) within 60 minutes .

The KPI dynamics are visualised through the dedicated R0/R1/R2/R3 panels over a 60-minute forecast horizon, in a deliberately narrow time window that aligns with the predictive-capacity signature used by the other pilots 
