6. Response Strategies
The model implements four strategies that vary along three dimensions: the vulnerability priority applied by responders, the dispatch topology (centralised vs. decentralised), and the routing algorithm in use 
R0 — Vulnerability-only / minimum-distance criterion: The responder base strategy that ignores the vulnerability priority and applies only the minimum distance criterion. It may yield acceptable aggregate rates but questionable outcomes in terms of actual casualty reduction, as it neglects the spatial distribution of those most at risk who remain stranded in zones with higher density or restricted access .
R1 — Vulnerability-aware central dispatch: Prioritises vulnerable group extraction. Faster and more steady evacuation rate than R0 especially after the 5-minute mark, but reaches only 30.77% of the vulnerable population within 60 minutes under the validation runs .
R2 — Balanced dispatch: Combined vulnerability + minimum-distance protocol under a centralised dispatch base. In this case study, this balanced strategy was not particularly effective .
R3 — Vulnerability-based, minimum-distance, A*-routed, near-port dispatch base: Decentralised dispatch avoids the bottleneck of a centralised evacuation base and pushes the vulnerable-population evacuation rate above 95% within 60 minutes R3 displays a remarkable effectiveness with the highest evacuation rate and the most stable gradient of improvement, with an evacuation rate notably surpassing that of the general population .
The cross-pilot summary in the source deliverable describes Odessa as producing the most decoupled responder behaviour under R3 — a finding that demonstrates the topology of the response fleet is reshaped, not just the routing of civilians .HOW TO USE IT
