Running a Trial
Open the UI and set the modal split, response delay, traffic pattern and vulnerability share .
Optionally revise the evacuation-point coordinates (assumed by default) 
Press Setup — residents populate shelters according to the local municipality mapping; stationary agents display road, building-passage, park-pathway and bomb-shelter nodes 
Press Go and wait for the evacuation rate curves over the 60-minute time window to stabilise; record R0 as the baseline 
Switch to R1 (vulnerability-aware central dispatch) and observe the curve's post-5-minute lift; capture the 60-minute percentage and compare to the documented 30.77% 
Switch to R2 — observe that the balanced strategy was not particularly effective in Odessa .
Switch to R3 (vulnerability-based + minimum-distance + A* + near-port dispatch); observe the >95% / 96% knockout result and the stable gradient of improvement 
THINGS TO NOTICE
R3 dominates the vulnerable-evacuation curve, not the total-evacuation curve. R3's evacuation rate notably surpasses that of the general population — meaning the marginal gain from decentralised dispatch is concentrated where it most matters: the vulnerable sub-KPI .
The post-5-minute inflection. R1 and R2 show a faster and more steady evacuation rate compared to R0, especially after the 5-minute mark, while R3 shows the most stable gradient of improvement The post-5-minute inflection is a structural property of responder deployment, not an artefact.
R0's casualty-reduction blind-spot. R0's aggregate evacuation rate can look acceptable, but ignoring the spatial distribution of those most at risk yields questionable outcomes in terms of actual casualty reduction . The map view will show vulnerable agents stranded in zones with higher density or restricted access.
Topology, not just routing, drives R3. The mechanism is explicitly structural: decentralised dispatch avoids the bottleneck of a centralised evacuation base, and pushes the vulnerable-population evacuation rate above 95% within 60 minutes .omparing R3 to R2 isolates the dispatch base as the cause — same routing, different topology .
Evacuation-point assumptions are user-influenceable. Because the evacuation points were assumed for modelling purposes, sensitivity to those coordinates is a useful experiment: rerunning with shifted coordinates tests the ablation of these coordinates that constrains the network-topology signal that R3 exploits .
The validation gap of 30.77% vs >95% discrimination. The source deliverable cites this gap as one of the lines of evidence that confirm the model correctly distinguishes between routing protocols .

The model never achieves net antifragility. Unlike Bratislava, the Odessa pilots, by prioritizing the redistribution or rerouting of existing assets, achieve significant adaptability but remain constrained by their baseline capacity . Notice that the post-evacuation throughput converges back toward baseline rather than exceeding it.
THINGS TO TRY
Stride the response selector from R0 → R1 → R2 → R3 under the same modal split, response delay and traffic pattern. You should see the documented 30.77% (R1) → 96% (R3) vulnerable-population gap open up at the 60-minute horizon 
Sweep the vulnerability-share slider from low to high and observe the exponential inflation of the vulnerable-population evacuation time in the do-nothing run .
Move the response-delay slider and observe the post-5-minute inflection shift under R1/R2/R3 — the inflection is delay-invariant in the structural sense, so the runtime of the responder fleet is what matters most .
Move the modal-split slider toward more pedestrians in R3 to test whether the evacuation rate notably surpassing that of the general population becomes even more pronounced — an experiment that probes the role of pedestrian mode in the network .
Sweep the traffic-pattern input upward and observe that A*-based rerouting retains efficiency under saturation — but narrow single-base dispatch (R0) yields fluctuating rates 
Ablate the evacuation-point coordinates by progressively moving them away from the documented location — you should reproduce the source deliverable's finding that ablation of these coordinates constrains the network-topology signal that R3 exploits .
Specifically try R2 to verify the documented under-performance — the model is consistent enough to expect this outcome under default input .
Map the responders' routes with the response selector set to R3 and confirm the near-port dispatch base signature, contrasting it with the centralised R1/R2 base.
EXTENDING THE MODEL
These extensions build directly on the documented limitations and design choices of the Odessa pilot 
Realistic evacuation coordinates. Replace the assumed evacuation-point coordinates with an actual city evacuation plan once it becomes available, eliminating the single most visible methodological caveat of the Odessa model .

Continuous reroute interval. The A* algorithm is invoked continuously, but this is currently unbounded in computational cost. Add a configurable replan-every-N-ticks interval so that the load under heavy congestion does not dominate the runtime .
Origin-aware responder dispatch. Currently responders use a single near-port dispatch base under R3 . Add an origin-aware dispatch for responders so that the structural advantage of R3 can be tested against alternative dispatch bases (e.g., nearest dispatch relative to vulnerability density).
Speed-velocity mapping. Currently vulnerable agents are assigned lower transit velocities (these are static) Add a calibrated mapping from vulnerability class to velocity, parameterised over the documented taxonomy (disabilities, mobility impairments, age extremes, disadvantaged and socio-economic backgrounds).
Crowd-dynamics at evacuation points. The model assumes evacuation-point throughput is unconstrained . Add a per-evacuation-point capacity constraint (stochastic saturating queue) to capture arrival-rate bottlenecks at the destination edge.
Heterogeneous response delay. Currently response delay is a single global parameter .dd a per-resident stochastic delay distribution so that the post-5-minute inflection is reproduced endogenously rather than only detected empirically .

Ablation-aware KPI. Currently the ablation of evacuation-point coordinates constrains the network-topology signal that R3 exploits . Add a quantification of this constraint by varying the coordinate noise seed in batch runs.
Multi-base responder dispatch (R4). R3 uses one near-port dispatch base; an extension could test a fully decentralised multi-base dispatch for further reduction of the central bottleneck.
Detailed-evacuation framework integration. Currently the simulation sits in the second phase of the evacuation plan only .dd a stub phase-1 "from home to shelter" transit to close the loop with the operational plan; this addition would also enable the model to be validated against documented empirical evacuation data once available.
NETLOGO FEATURES
Dynamic breed transformation (resident → pedestrian / car). The defining structural trick: ask residents [if mode-chosen? [become one-of turtles-with breed "pedestrian"]]. This is a clean NetLogo workaround for the specification's resident-to-(pedestrian-or-car) transformation rule that simply keeps both dynamic breeds co-existing with no agents of either pre-discharge .
Multi-agent-class ontology in a single world. Residents, pedestrians, cars, all three stationary breeds (intersections, shelters, evacuation points), and a fifth dynamic breed — responders — coexist in one world and updated on the same tick .

Network primitives (links to nodes). Because the graph is composed of link-owned edges plus stationary nodes that hold shelter and evacuation-point state, the model uses NetLogo's network extension with a multi-breed nodeset .
view-updates-driven evacuation plot panel. R0/R1/R2/R3 each get a dedicated panel showing total and vulnerable cumulative evacuation trajectories, plotted as paired cumulative counts . Aingle panel would be cluttered in evacuation contexts, so each strategy gets its own until R3 is selected and sits alongside the previous runs.
A\* semantics via path-finding reporter (network extension). The continuous re-evaluation of trajectories under real-time road accessibility shifts such as path obstructions or saturation is implemented by a per-tick replan that consumes the current edge-cost table .

atch-based shelter locations. Bomb-shelter capacities from the local-municipality data are stored as both stationary-agent state and as a patch-level overlay; this enables an easy lookup during the A* call and saves memory for high-capacity shelter classifications .

Stochasticity via random-normal and random-float. Vulnerability class is sampled once at agent birth, and response delay is sampled once per resident from random-float to mirror the stochastic head-start condition .
Composite response procedure. R0/R1/R2/R3 each have distinct (vulnerability-priority flag, dispatch-base location, routing-protocol flag) tuples that the apply-response reporter branches on, the same low-code composite used by the other pilots, adapted to Odessa's responder-only response family 
60-minute forecast horizon snapshot. A single ticks = 3600 constant in the go procedure captures the documented 60-minute forecast horizon for KPI reporting (1, 37, 73, …, 577 ticks at the documented cadence), the same operational logic used by the Bratislava pilot but in seconds-resolution 
Evacuation-point ablation by per-tile perturbation. Because the rendered evacuation points were assumed, they are stored in a evacuation-points-list of patches that the user can perturb seed by seed, allowing the documented ablation experiment to be reproduced from the UI .
